<typeStatus box="[151,249,1755,1781]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">holotype</typeStatus>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Perkins, P. D. &amp; Ribera, I." box="[308,570,1755,1781]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" pagination="35 - 52" refId="ref3201" refString="Perkins, P. D. &amp; Ribera, I. (2020) Three new species and DNA sequence data of the rare South American water beetle genus Adelphydraena Perkins, 1989 (Coleoptera: Hydraenidae). Zootaxa, 4858 (1), 35 - 52. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4858.1.2" type="journal article" year="2020">Perkins &amp; Ribera 2020</bibRefCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[588,1333,1754,1781]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[588,936,1754,1781]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Terminal abdominal segments</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[991,1147,1754,1781]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">spermatheca:</emphasis>
Terminal tergite
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1348,1428,1755,1781]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1903,1927]" captionTargetBox="[188,1431,638,1837]" captionTargetId="figure-213@4.[151,1436,596,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Female of Adelphydraena amazonica Perkins &amp; Ribera, terminal tergite (a), last abdominal ventrite (b) and spermatheca (c, d). Scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4729449" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4729449/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Fig. 3a</figureCitation>
) elliptical. Disc covered by short setae and with distal margin slightly emarginated. Last abdominal ventrite (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1903,1927]" captionTargetBox="[188,1431,638,1837]" captionTargetId="figure-213@4.[151,1436,596,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Female of Adelphydraena amazonica Perkins &amp; Ribera, terminal tergite (a), last abdominal ventrite (b) and spermatheca (c, d). Scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4729449" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4729449/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Fig. 3b</figureCitation>
) with two plates. Ventral plate heart-shaped, without subapical tufts of setae. Dorsal plate slightly asymmetrical, surpassing the proximal rim of ventral plate and with two slightly impressed elliptical depressions. 
<emphasis box="[1290,1436,1863,1889]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Spermatheca</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[159,271,1899,1926]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1903,1927]" captionTargetBox="[188,1431,638,1837]" captionTargetId="figure-213@4.[151,1436,596,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Female of Adelphydraena amazonica Perkins &amp; Ribera, terminal tergite (a), last abdominal ventrite (b) and spermatheca (c, d). Scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4729449" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4729449/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Figs 3c, d</figureCitation>
) distinctly long, straight and distally capitate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1719,2033]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,440,1935,1961]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Sexual dimorphism.</emphasis>
Male (
<figureCitation box="[523,583,1935,1962]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1955,1979]" captionTargetBox="[279,1411,211,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-21@2.[175,1412,181,1931]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Male of Adelphydraena amazonica Perkins &amp; Ribera. Dorsal (a), lateral (b) and ventral (c) habitus. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4729445" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4729445/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Fig.1</figureCitation>
) similar to female in external morphology (compare with 
<figureCitation box="[1247,1314,1935,1961]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1612,1636]" captionTargetBox="[171,1367,222,1554]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[169,1419,181,1589]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male of Adelphydraena amazonica Perkins &amp; Ribera, aedeagus in lateral (a) and ventral (b) view, sternite X and spiculum gastrale (c). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4729447" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4729447/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[1300,1314,1935,1961]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" unit="in" value="2.0">2</quantity>
</figureCitation>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Perkins, P. D. &amp; Ribera, I." pageId="3" pageNumber="64" pagination="35 - 52" refId="ref3201" refString="Perkins, P. D. &amp; Ribera, I. (2020) Three new species and DNA sequence data of the rare South American water beetle genus Adelphydraena Perkins, 1989 (Coleoptera: Hydraenidae). Zootaxa, 4858 (1), 35 - 52. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4858.1.2" type="journal article" year="2020">Perkins &amp; Ribera, 2020</bibRefCitation>
), but smaller (ca. 1.38-1.45 x 
<quantity box="[666,824,1971,1998]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.75" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="7.5" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="0.775" valueMax="0.8" valueMin="0.75">0.75-0.80 mm</quantity>
opposite to female ca. 1.50-1.51 x 
<quantity box="[1221,1381,1971,1997]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.35" metricValueMax="8.4" metricValueMin="8.299999999999999" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="0.835" valueMax="0.84" valueMin="0.83">0.83-0.84 mm</quantity>
) and with elytral margins slightly wider than in female. Tibiae without sexually dimorphic characters.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,446,150,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="65">Taxonomic remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins &amp; Ribera. Reserva Florestal Ducke, Manaus County" authorityYear="2020" box="[453,753,150,176]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Adelphydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis box="[453,753,150,176]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="65">Adelphydraena amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a characteristic chordate pronotum and a developed serrate elytral margin and thus, resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins &amp; Ribera" authorityYear="2020" box="[591,770,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Adelphydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="surinamensis">
<emphasis box="[591,770,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="65">A. surinamensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins &amp; Ribera" authorityYear="2020" box="[824,941,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Adelphydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis box="[824,941,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="65">A. spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It also resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1989" box="[1149,1286,186,213]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Adelphydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spangleri">
<emphasis box="[1149,1286,186,213]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="65">A. spangleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but this species is considerably bigger and lacks serrate elytral margins. Conversely, the male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins &amp; Ribera. Reserva Florestal Ducke, Manaus County" authorityYear="2020" box="[1206,1358,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Adelphydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis box="[1206,1358,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="65">A. amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1989" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Adelphydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spangleri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="65">A. spangleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar, especially their main pieces. Based on morphological similarities these four species seem to be closely related, while the fifth known species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1989" box="[670,827,294,321]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Adelphydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orchymonti">
<emphasis box="[670,827,294,321]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="65">A. orchymonti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, has a slightly diverging shape. This is congruent with the partial phylogenetic arrangement based on molecular data revealed in 
<bibRefCitation author="Perkins, P. D. &amp; Ribera, I." box="[979,1258,330,356]" pageId="4" pageNumber="65" pagination="35 - 52" refId="ref3201" refString="Perkins, P. D. &amp; Ribera, I. (2020) Three new species and DNA sequence data of the rare South American water beetle genus Adelphydraena Perkins, 1989 (Coleoptera: Hydraenidae). Zootaxa, 4858 (1), 35 - 52. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4858.1.2" type="journal article" year="2020">Perkins &amp; Ribera (2020)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="65" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,497,366,392]" pageId="4" pageNumber="65">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
Specimens were collected in the type-locality of the species, a shaded forest stream at “Ducke Forest Reserve”, nearby Manaus city, Amazonas, 
<collectingCountry box="[832,904,402,428]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="65">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. This typical Amazonian stream is a permanent creek (
<figureCitation box="[227,309,438,464]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1640,1664]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-19@5.[151,1435,181,1617]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Habitat of Adelphydraena amazonica Perkins &amp; Ribera. Reserva Florestal Ducke, Manaus County, Amazonas State, Brazil. Igarapé Acará (a) and associated lateral swampy pool (b) where the specimens were collected." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4729451" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4729451/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="65">Fig. 4a</figureCitation>
), which exhibits seasonal water level fluctuations. During the rainy season, the water table increases significantly, frequently overflowing the stream banks and creating lateral swamp pools. The three reported specimens were collected in a temporal lateral pool, close to the stream banks (
<figureCitation box="[999,1084,510,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1640,1664]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-19@5.[151,1435,181,1617]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Habitat of Adelphydraena amazonica Perkins &amp; Ribera. Reserva Florestal Ducke, Manaus County, Amazonas State, Brazil. Igarapé Acará (a) and associated lateral swampy pool (b) where the specimens were collected." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4729451" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4729451/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="65">Fig. 4b</figureCitation>
), filled stream water, leaf litter and exposed roots.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
